caption: Excellent food and service. Everyone was respectful and masked, giving plenty of notice when they would approach the table for water refills, take orders, etc. Tables spaced out appropriately, and copious heaters outdoors.

Electic mix of french inspired cuisine, serving the aftter work crowd and locals. Perfect to see and be seen.

We went last weekend, and it was the most depressing restaurant experience I’ve had during this entire pandemic. I want to support restaurants, I love great food and great environments, and I appreciate the challenges facing restaurants at this time, but I will be haunted for some time by the poor everything that we experienced — food, ambiance, service, etc. I won’t be able to go to another restaurant for some time, it was so...bad.

Experienced Mintwood Place during Winter '21 Restaurant Week, during an early dinner reservation.  Highlights: - a creamy and flavorful ricotta starter with fresh, crisp bread - my girlfriend's generously-portioned and fall-off-the-bone tender lamb shank - hot and tasty mulled cider  Lowlights: - the restaurant has two outdoor patios, one directly outside the restaurant equipped with large heat lamps, and one under a tent that left much to be desired with small, ineffective heaters (most of which were lacking propane fuel). we were seated at the latter setup, and unfortunately it was no better than if we were eating in the open air in 30 degree weather. - a tasty mushroom soup that unfortunately came plated in a large, shallow dish which meant that it went from piping hot to lukewarm in just a couple of minutes in the cold of patio dining - a duck entree brimming with sauerkraut and mostarda but light on the actual duck and accompanying fingerling potatoes  Hats off to Mintwood for a Restaurant Week menu brimming with choice (n.b. short rib unfortunately was sold out during our dinner), a feat during the current business environment. To offer some constructive feedback, if the outdoor patio seating won't be heated as advertised, please communicate with customers beforehand so they can arrive armed with more blankets and/or gloves.

Another great Restaurant Week takeout meal. First courses of endive salad and mushroom soup were outstanding. We both had the five-spiced chicken, also outstanding and enough for two meals. Desserts of two different pastries were a wonderful end to the meal.

Went for restaurant week brunch. Mushroom soup & corned beef.  The mushroom soup is savory and accompanied with cocoa for some interesting bitter tastes.  The corned beef is also lovely, hits all the flavor notes without the often insane amounts of salt other places like to drop in...can actually taste things!  Also tried their chicken fried steak with grits. I can see why this place is fantastic, looking forward to returning.  COVID precautions: 25% interior seating, every seat gets a screen to reduce airflow relative to the other parts of the bar. Wear your mask when not eating, nobody else deserves to find out the hard way you brought covid.  PARKING IS TRICKY. Arrive early. Eat well.
I recommend ordering the Parts and Labor cocktail. The reason for 3-stars is the food wasn’t worth the price.
Menu limited compared to pre covid which is understandable. However as opposed to many restaurants in DC they were able to the high quality of their dishes. Would definitely recommend them.
I regret not coming here sooner. Shout out Hank for serving a great meal, highlighted by the steak tartare and lamb shank. Not a disappointing moment throughout. Cheers.
Good on Thanksgiving. Lots of outdoor seating, great atmosphere. Thanks to wait staff for making it an enjoyable meal.

I was ready to leave this place a stellar review but my experience closing my check was cringeworthy. I gave the waiter my card to close my check for $124 for brunch and I left him a $40 cash tip. Then the person who had been bussing my table came and took the check. The person then returned and asked that I sign the bill even though I had already left a more than substantial tip. After signing it and putting “cash” in the tip section, the waiter returned clearly under the impression that I had stiffed him and says “ I think maybe I had taken this too early?” Grabbing the attention of half of the patio who is now looking at me as if I would not tip the wait staff. I told him that his fellow server or maybe bus boy had grabbed the check at first and I told him the amount that I actually left. Either way I left feeling embarrassed because of the negative attention he brought to me. Maybe it’s because I’m black he assumed I would not tip him? Either way I won’t be returning.

Worst restaurant experience I have ever had. Please don’t go here if you want to enjoy yourself and the people you genuinely value.  I deeply care about being cautious about spreading COVID-19. I took my mask off to take a sip of water and was aggressively approached by the hostess to leave the restaurant because my views did not align with his. As a female, I felt personally attacked and I don’t want anyone else to feel like this on a night they planned to enjoy with the people closest to them.

Charming neighborhood bistro -- friendly and knowledgeable staff, interesting wine list and consistently excellent ragu. Additional props for the sound proofing (foam under the tables) - you can easily hold a conversation, even when the restaurant is full (seems like a lifetime ago now). Thanks Mintwood!

Mintwood Place is an oasis in the desert that has been this year. In days of yore, back in 2019 BC (Before Covid), we would vacillate between the cosy window nooks and the welcoming bar, where pressing questions of the day would be addressed; ‘is that Matt or Matthew tending bar tonight and where does Tim get those shirts?’  In more modern times, in 2020 AD (After Disease), they cautiously reopened but protecting the good health of staff and patrons alike has always been their guiding principle. All the more noteworthy then, that they miraculously maintain the excellent standard of cuisine for which they have ever been known. So now we dress for the Arctic but are quickly warmed by the sunny outlooks of all who work there, plus the occasional mulled libation. And patio heaters.  Well done Mintwood!
Excellent food and warm heaters outside. We went with a group and ordered almost everything. It was all exceptional. We'll definitely be back soon.

Our favorite restaurant in DC. Covered outdoor seating area, great service, and delicious food (lamb shank is A+). If you sit outside, the neighborhood can be a bit loud and busy (it’s a happening area). Inside can be a bit loud too because it’s pretty compact. Well worth a visit - be sure to make a reservation.
Great food. Fun drinks. Continually changing menu. The staff is knowledgeable. A bit pricey but worth it.

Mintwood is consistently one of our favorite neighborhood spots. The food is fantastic, the service is quick and friendly.

Mintwood's food is consistently delightful, from comforting winter Bolognese to refreshing summer gazpacho.  The staff are wonderful and the wine list is excellent (the manager is a former sommelier).  It's quickly become a favorite neighborhood spot and we look forward to trying each new menu item.

We ordered delivery from Mintwood to celebrate our anniversary. It was delicious! We did the 2 person dinner and added on an additional entree, which was plenty of food for two. For appetizers we had the white gazpacho and the watermelon salad; for entrees, the rigatoni and the linguisa (sp?); and for dessert, the chocolate mousse. All were great choices and worked well with delivery. I love that they use their own people for delivery - driver was professional and looked like maybe one of the wait staff. We ordered for 6:30 and it arrived at 6:29. The hot food was hot and the cold was cold. It was perfect!

The wine was a $10 bottle marked up to $40, which is expected, but usually that stings a bit less when the food wows us. Service was quite good, however, and the experience was overall fine.

We went to brunch at Mintwood Place on 3/3 and unfortunately other than our server, Jheneal, the experience was less than enjoyable.  Our party ended up being larger than expected. And I will admit this can be frustrating for the restaurant, the way my friend was treated by (who I am going to assume is) the manager, Gene, was very unappealing by a restaurant manager. Gene rudely leaned over our table and all but lectured a group of women trying to get brunch. He didn't check on us at all after the seating fiasco, and refused to budge on giving us another table. As a former server, I watched the tables around us and there was an empty table near us for over an hour after we had ordered. It was obvious he was just unwilling to accommodate the change.  Although the experience with Gene will keep any of us from returning to the restaurant, our server was very lovely and attentive. She was fun, interacted with and checked on us, made sure everyone had drinks, split our bill the way we asked, etc. Jheneal made the experience for us.  If the manager had been more friendly, even without being able to accommodate the change I would give Mintwood Place 5 stars and return. Unfortunately there are too many amazing places to eat in DC that also have great management.
Excellent food but a bit loud on a Friday night for conversation .
Very good happy hour food and drinks. The chicken liver pate and onion soup are delicious.  Warm fresh bread served, too.
Great place for brunch, we tried most of the appetizers; they were delicious and had great presentation. The entree's were also very good and the presentation was great.

This place is everything!! I'm a picky eater; was never a fan of French food, but they changed my mind. The waitress Ryan is such a sweetheart. His recommendations are very honest and trust worthy. So If  he says this is good, please believe it! He let me know this is basically French comfort food. There was nothing I disliked, from the drinks, to the appetizer, my meal, and even dessert. I tried medium well for the first time, and I have now been converted! This is the first time I can say me going to a restaurant was an experience. If u want happy hour, it's strictly at the bar. You have to get there when doors open. We got there at 6/6:30 Fri night, and it was full. The ambiance is nice and cozy, matching the theme of what's served. What I really appreciate is, the service isn't rushed after your meal. Most restaurants will rush you to leave when you finish eating, but not these folks.  They deserve every great review they received in the newspaper. I will definitely go again.

Chef Matt Cockrell with an amazing menu! We started with an assortment of nibbles that did not disappoint.  The stand out was the Charcuterie Board: Selection of Cured Meats & Chicken Liver Mousse also amazing was the White Peach & Balsamic Soup, Goat Cheese, Crouton.  The food was simply fresh and clean, which took American fare to another level.  We pretty much tried the whole menu but the real stand outs of the evening were the Branzino, Pearl Couscous, Tomato and the Tagliatelle Bolognese, Pecorino with an honorable mention to the Wood-Grilled, Dry-Aged Bacon Cheeseburger, Fries.  But for me the Branzino was the superstar of the show.  Light, buttery, and so much flavor, would definitely order that dish again.  Overall the staff was friendly, the atmosphere was lively yet quiet enough to hold a conversation; ideal for a small dinner party or a date night.  This restaurant will definitely be added to our GO TO list whenever we are in the city!  Can't wait to try Brunch ....

1) Steak and egg (yes, egg) for brunch were TINY. The smallest little nugget of meat I've ever seen. Not filling in the slightest and for the extremely overpriced rate of $19.  2) No bread served with pate. Who wants just spoonfuls of meat?  3) We had to ask for a soup spoon despite numerous employees seeing us futiley try to eat with the spoon provided for coffee.  4) Tea kettles were served about 10 minutes prior to actually getting tea cups.  5) Someone stole my girlfriend's umbrella.  6) A mimosa was missing from the table until just before the meal was finished.  7) One of the loudest restaurants I've ever been. Yelling is necessary for conversations at the same table.  We've been for dinner and we've been for brunch. Will never return for either.
Not cheap but good food and service

What's not to love? The food is creative, bountiful and scrumptious. The service is solicitous, affable and attentive. The room is whimsical and festive. Superlative, in every regard, every time. Bravo!

It was the loudest restaurant we have ever eaten. Prices are $1-2 higher than it should be. Service was spotty. If you don't drink coffee, they just leave the cups on the tables. SOO unhygienic.
Great neighborhood place with an ever-changing menu.  Good for vegetarians and carnivores alike.  Charming interior with attentive well trained service staff.  A great place for a great meal.

Me and my bf love this place for the first time, great food and services. My favorite is Kale salad-very recommended. Plus, strawberry shortcake is the best for dessert-not too sweet.

Excellent service. Phenominal food.

While the food is good, the atmosphere is loud and the crowd can be immature. Not for sophisticated tastes in this regard, and reflects more of the unruly side of Adams Morgan than necessary, considering the prices on the menu.
Sunday Brunch was enjoyed by all.

We were given a free app as we waited, and once we were sat our waitress was prompt and wonderful. Some of our party had food allergies and the waitress was very knowledgeable about the food, and asked the kitchen when she wasn't sure about something. Even though it was incredibly busy (we did come on a Saturday night though) the atmosphere was great and we were all taken care of (our waters never went empty). It was well worth the wait for our table!

My husband and I were spending a very chilly winter evening in Adams Morgan and stumbled upon this lovely little spot. Just a peek through the curtained front door and we knew it was for us. It's a perfectly cozy and approachable french bistro featuring all the favorite dishes. We shared the onion soup—my favorite and it was incredible—and continued the traditional choices with Steak & Frites and Saffron Mussel Chowder—both SO good. Our server made excellent wine suggestions and were so pleased with everything. We can't wait to go back, probably in nicer weather to try the patio seating.

Tasty and diverse menu.

Amazing happy hour, go try it! $5 glass of wine of a great quality, and extensive food menu significantly cheaper than during regular time, very nice waiters, a classy and nice crowd of people go there. I loved it. The menu outside of happy hour is pricey, but it is worth it. One of my favorite restaurants

Cold butter, definitely not salt. The decor was really nice and the risotto was good. Beef bourguignon was quite dry. We also didn't have a wait staff for 10 minutes and one didn't come until I talked to the host.

What a fantastic spot! Almost a 1920s aesthetic with a beautiful menu. Delicious coffee and a huge variety of cheeses. I had the Norwegian eggs Benedict and the eggs were slightly overdone. But the hollandaise was perfect.

God, what a nightmare. Went here with my parents for what turned out to be brunch—ok, I get it, brunch is popular for some reason. But this place took all the things that annoy anti-brunchers like me and amplified them: inescapable din created by drunk people shouting across the table at each other, check. Ridiculously over-priced eggs dressed up as gourmet experiences (and an $18 hamburger?!?), check. Inattentive and mediocre service (had to ask multiple times for things like cream for coffee, water, and utensils). Super-slow kitchen--we must have spent at least 45 min waiting for food.  Again, I get that brunch is popular, and the place was packed on a cold Sunday. But if Mintwood is going to present itself as a destination for high-end hipster brunch—with prices to match—they should be better prepared to handle that.

Good food. Good service.

Decent service decent food.  A couple of dishes were not warm, but staff did their  best to resolve our issues. I would go back. The beef, fries and dessert were very good.
Mintwood has a cool atmosphere, tasty food and good service. I didn't love the cocktail I had, but they were quick to make me a new one. All in all, good location and nice spot!

Mintwood has great food in a casual atmosphere. The service is always great and they do a nice happy hour with discount cocktails and food in the bar area. Great neighborhood place to grab a bite to eat and relax.

This place is really unique in Adams Morgan. Great food, atmosphere, and service. Our waiter, Dejan, was just wonderful.

Went for restaurant week - it was amazing.  Sometimes, restaurant week options leave you feeling like you didn't get a full meal, more of a sample, which is, of course, completely fine and a restaurant's prerogative.  Mintwood, however, leaves you with no question that you received an amazingly prepared meal, full of rich, wholesome foods,  for a steal of a price.  Highly recommend - I'll be back next year!
The food and service are fantastic.

Went for NYE dinner. Can't believe it took me so long to eat here! Interesting and varied menu with well crafted, mouth-watering dishes and friendly service. The mocktails were delicious as was dessert.
Excellent farm to table food.
My family ate here for Thanksgiving: wow. Amazing food for every course, especially desserts.
it is good
Really bad
Great ambience and some interesting selections. Nice to find that quality hasn't been replaced with quantity everywhere. Would recommend and would go back.
Overall pretty tasty but I was not a fan of my entree but everything else was 4 stars.
Fun place.  They have a great dry aged, wood fire grilled burger that I would recommend.  Good drink selection as well
One of my favorite places in the city!!
Pleasant vibe, great house cocktails! Loud and fun!

The BF and I decided upon Mintwood Place for Winter Restaurant Week 2016. We were not disappointed at all!  The menu online is different than the one they gave us, but we ordered the steak tartare and escargot hush puppies as appetizers, a tomato braised lamb rigatoni and veal schnitzel as the entree, and an orange-chocolate pot de creme and key lime pie as desserts. Everything was amazing!! I especially loved the desserts. I could eat the pot de creme and key lime pie forever and ever.  The service was great (very accommodating to my taste in wine) and the decor was rustic and not too cramped.

Some of the best service in DC, be sure to get their Meatballs with fromage blanc. I never thought cheese could taste that awesome. My friend got their ribs and those easily beat Fat Pete's, Rockland's, and Kangaroo in DC as the best ribs.

Pretentious rudeness loses my business every time. Came here after 6pm on a windy and cloudy Wednesday, and the patio was COMPLETELY empty. Literally 30 empty seats outside and almost totally empty inside.  Was meeting one friend and I asked to sit outside. They refused and said, "we'll only seat you when the other person arrives".  I can understand this stuff on a sunny Thursday on 14th street and a party of six where one person shows, but not in some random street off upper Adams Morgan when someone asks for a table for two at am empty restaurant.
The escargot hush-puppies are AMAZING.
Good
Great restaurant. The menu is well balanced and the food is great. Always a good place to go to have a good meal.

We went for brunch on Saturday at 11:30ish. It was fairly busy and service was somewhat slow, but we did in the bar, and the server was good.  The eggs were greasy diner quality, the bacon was bad, but the potatoes and toast/apple butter were good.
Amazing for brunch, also it's a fun Friday or Saturday night.

Dinner is much better than their brunch (they're way too strict on substitutions), but I'm not sure it's worth the dime. Their key lime pie was my dinner's highlight. It's a good option for restaurant week.

Mintwood Place is amazing.  It is consistently a wonderful, warm environment that feels very welcoming on any night.  While it's sometimes hard to find a reservation, I've had surprising luck walking in to a table.  The appetizers are a clear gem on the menu; vegetarians should try the kale and burrata, while carnivores might like the steak tartare.  The entrees change seasonally and with availability, but it's consistently excellent.  There is the rare item that is oversalted, but after years of coming here, it's pretty rare.  One of my favorite restaurants in DC (and was an Obama dinner date once, too). :)

A solid 5 stars. My wife and I went here to celebrate a job promotion and we walked out grateful we didn't go anywhere else. We ordered drinks off the bat and were impressed. If you like sweeter drinks, order the Clover Club. My wife ordered the Foggy London Town and loved it as well. As you sip your drinks, they bring out a warm basket of bread with salt butter. AMAZING!  For an appetizer, we ordered the the burrata, kales, hazelnut, apple & tamarind. It was one of the best appetizers I've had in DC and they even equally split it on two dishes for us.  For our main course, we both ordered the cheeseburger and it was one of the best burgers I've had in DC with crisp bacon and a perfectly toasted bun. Two things to note: 1) It's very easy to eat. Some burgers are so messy to eat, but this one perfectly fit together making it easy to eat, and 2) It tasted like a gourmet Big Mac. I don't say that to scare people away, but if McDonald's turned their classic Big Mac into a gourmet burger for the President, this would be it.  Definitely go here next time you want to celebrate an occasion!
Creative entrees - everything done perfectly & so tasty!
Good drinks.

Here to inform out of towners regarding the absolute lack of hospitality at this establishment. Walked in with my daughter, saw empty tables, and was told that "open table" had possible reservations that "could" show up. There is something to be said for person to person customer service. I've experienced that this novel concept has gone the way of the dinosaur in Washington DC. I lived here for 14 years. I am now very glad that I left.

Will not return. This is the first negative review I have ever taken the time to write on a restaurant, but as the interaction was this unpleasant I felt it was needed.  I had made advanced reservations for a special occasion (birthday) at Mintwood Place. Midway through our appetizers an alarm sounded. This alarm was very loud and made conversation near impossible. It sounded another three times before our waiter informed us that they were forced to close for the evening due to kitchen issues. This is understandable and I am not unsympathetic to the issue, but we were handed our bill and treated with very little compassion, having had our plans ruined. Not a single item was comped and the apology seemed much less than genuine. I chalked this up to the panic of the moment and made a mental note to contact a manager later to reconcile the issue. I did so, but the reception I received was more apathetic than the initial experience. The response (from the manager) was that it was "beyond their control", and that it is the "price of doing business". I'm sorry, but I have now paid full price for items at a restaurant, for a meal I could not converse during large portions of due to your alarm system, was rushed out the door without finishing, given apathetic treatment, then told that this is the "price of doing business" with you? Well if that is the case I will certainly not be returning. As an establishment that considers itself to be high-end and aims to deliver a fulfilling experience I did not expect this. You delivered an experience, but it is one I do not care to ever repeat. If you value a business that treats clients with respect then this is not the one for you.
Good food, bad acoustics
Consistent and tasty food and appetizers. A good beer selection and a fairly large wine list. On each of my visits I have had great service from start to finish and loved every dish I've ordered.

Mintwood Place has a great brunch with spot-on service.  I was there recently and had the "hangover special" which is a hamburger and onions, covered in cheddar fries, topped with bacon and a sunny-side up egg.  Perfection.

I love this place, the food is always amazing and has a great atmosphere. I prefer the vibe during the weekdays when you can sit a the bar and have a conversation with the staff. all funny and pleasant.
Went during restaurant week and was blown away by the amazing food and dining experience.  Will go back soon!!
It was absolutely delicious! We went there for restaurant week and had the Burrata, Pork Chop and Bucatini bolognese- they were amazing! Would definitely come back here :)
Amazing food, great atmosphere. By far the best place in the neighborhood and among the best in the city. Get the steak tartar and the kale salad.

Good fresh food with a SUPER DUPER friendly atomosphere. I've been here about 12 times, for brunch no less (yikes! lol), and they have yet to dissapoint. The pancakes especially will have you coming back for more....... The wait staff and managers know me and my friends and  we are equally as happy to see each other with each visit. It's like our  very own personal Cheers.:)  I haven't made it for dinner yet but I see that in future.  You will not be dissapointed, check em out!

As enticing as the menu is, execution falls flat. Dishes are decent but nothing special. Cucumber gazpacho is fresh and clean; fried kale and burrata salad is tasty. Prepare to wait for a table, even if you're on time for your reservation. Wait staff is friendly.
Food was stunning. Cocktails were inventive.  Service was outstanding.  Fantastic!

I'd like to describe my experience, but I can't. Mintwood Place doesn't want my business. I often dine out alone, and when I tried to make a reservation for Mintwood Place, there was nothing available. On a whim, I tried to see what happened if I was reserving for 2. Suddenly there were slots open all over the place.  Thanks but no thanks Mintwood Place.
Ambience, food service was fabulous!  Bar scene was terrific.  So enjoyable.
A trendy bar with a sort of dressy casual feel.  Great food but for two you'll spend close to $100.

Excellent restaurant with a nice cozy feel. They have a great wine and beer selection. The bartenders were excellent.  The pickled devil eggs were incredible as was the burger and chicken. Both were incredibly juicy and full of flavor. The only mediocre part of the whole meal were the fries. Everything else was above and beyond.

Beautiful room, great bartender and excellent cocktails (including a few never-before-seen bourbon concoctions--a rarity).  Apps are well portioned, tasty, and beautifully presented.  Entrees appear hit-or-miss.  Salmon was simple, elegant, masterfully prepared; chicken, while well-prepared, was drab and monotonous.  To much of one thing.  Wine list is extensive, but offers little under $60.  Recommended.  Reservation necessary on weekend.
I love this place!  Great food, good wine list and knowledgable servers.  A gem.
Had a fabulous, fabulous dinner here. Have you ever been scared off by a particular ingredient? Trust the chefs here -- they'll make it right, and you'll love it. Plus, wow, the COCKTAILS!
Nothing stood out- except the salt! There was no detection of corn in the escargot hush puppies- what a bummer :( We saw Mike Isabella there last night; hopefully he had a better experience.
